===Etymology 1===
Late 17th century, of {{unk|en|title=unknown}} origin, possibly allied to {{cog|cy|moedro|t=to worry or bother}}. Alternatively, possibly tied to {{cog|cy|meidda|t=to beg for whey}} or perhaps {{m|cy|meiddio|t=to dare or venture}}. Bear in mind that the "dd" in Welsh corresponds in sound to the "th" in mither, and English also has [[moider]] and [[moither]].

====Pronunciation====
* {{IPA|en|/ˈmaɪðəɹ/}}
* {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Vealhurl-mither.wav |Audio (UK)}}

====Verb====
{{en-verb|mithers|mithering|mithered|mithered}}

# {{lb|en|intransitive|Northern England}} To make an [[unnecessary]] [[fuss]], [[moan]], [[bother]].
#: ''The European Commission is pondering how to compel phone companies to come up with a universal plug for their chargers. Apple, which uses its own design for its charger cables, is '''mithering''' about the change.'' ("The parable of the plug", ''The Economist'', 6 February 2020)
# {{lb|en|transitive|Northern England}} To [[pester]] or [[irritate]] someone. Usually directed at [[children]].
#: ''Will you stop '''mithering''' me!''

